yes -- OpenVINO is the obvious thing to test on that machine.

short answer

for a 2021 Intel MBP, OpenVINO has a decent chance of being faster than plain ONNX Runtime CPU, because OpenVINO’s CPU plugin is specifically tuned for Intel x86-64 CPUs, and ONNX Runtime also has an OpenVINO execution provider if you want to stay inside ORT. OpenVINO docs still support macOS CPU inference on x86_64, while on macOS the package support is CPU-only.  ￼

what it is

openvino = intel inference runtime / optimizer

good at:
	•	Intel CPU
	•	quantized models
	•	tuned threading / scheduling
	•	squeezing more from x86 than generic CPU runtimes

not magic:
	•	it will not turn an Intel MBP into a 4090
	•	it will not solve your determinism questions by itself

why it is relevant for your machine

OpenVINO’s CPU device path is explicitly for Intel x86-64 CPUs, and its performance hints / thread scheduling are designed to auto-tune to the CPU architecture. That is exactly the sort of thing that can beat a plain, untuned ORT CPU path on Intel laptop hardware.  ￼

Also, OpenVINO still documents building and running on macOS Intel CPU systems, which is a good sign for your exact setup.  ￼

two ways to use it

1. easiest Beast experiment

Keep your app mostly the same and try:

onnx runtime + openvino execution provider

ORT has an OpenVINO EP, so you may be able to stay within your current ONNX-based architecture while testing Intel-optimized execution.  ￼

2. more direct

Test native OpenVINO runtime on the model directly.

That may give you a cleaner picture of OpenVINO performance, but it is a slightly bigger integration fork.

what to expect

On your current baseline:

512x512
20 steps
sd1.5 onnx raw
254s

I would treat OpenVINO as a maybe meaningful, not guaranteed dramatic speedup.

Realistically, best-case on that class of machine might be something like:

254s → mabe 150–220s

with a bigger win possible only if:
	•	your current ORT setup is very untuned
	•	model conversion / graph handling improves a lot
	•	threading was poor before

I would not assume a miracle like 254s → 30s on that machine.

beast recommendation

This is the right order:

1. tune onnx runtime cpu first
2. test openvino ep
3. compare artifact + timing logs
4. keep whichever wins cleanly

because then Beast learns something real instead of just accumulating backend lore.

clean mental model

plain ort cpu = baseline
ort + openvino ep = intel-optimized test
nvidia workstation = real heavy compute target

my blunt take

for your 2021 Intel MBP:

openvino = worth testing
not worth betting the whole architecture on

it is a smart optimization experiment, not the final answer.

